doc.field: Rector and Visitors of the University of Virginia
Vickery, Robert L. (American architect and university professor)

The line between 'home' and 'public space' and 'place' is not as clear in these rural communities at the time of the photo. Probably not much has changed but would be curious what this area looked like today. At the time of these photos, RLV described his initial interest was really focused on the public space being a 'studio' to build pots for a local festival in which people would purchase pots to 'throw down and break during a celebration' only to be recycled again for a future use/celebration. The pots he noted were well made, almost perfect in symmetry despite the hand held and crude tools used to spin the pots. The artisan stacked the pots on end creating 'racks' of pots that overtook the public space of this small settlement. The importance of art and decorative elements in everyday life in the poorest of communities never ceased to fascinate RLV from India, to China, to Spain or Cambodia. Capturing the culture of each place he visited was as important as the buildings in that most of the time one informed the other and could be found in the details of the art, the buildings and their design. -- Robert L. Vickery

The walkway is lined now with trees and is a pedestrian pathway from the fields and parking lots below. It leads into the school's central green and the art classroom. At the time of the development, this feature was unusual for a public school. The campus pays attention to the grade of the land to create maximum use of the elevations and access to classrooms varying by the age of the students. -- Robert L. Vickery

The entryway to the school was based on a Palladian design where the door was not on center but on either sides of a central column. The entire school was broken down into a series of balanced parts off of a central 'green' with an 'art room' that extends out from the orderly plan. The library 'floats' above the entrance; the round windows signal at the entrance the special nature of the library function in education. -- Robert L. Vickery

The line between 'home' and 'public space' and 'place' is not as clear in these rural communities at the time of the photo. Probably not much has changed but would be curious what this area looked like today. At the time of these photos, RLV described his initial interest was really focused on the public space being a 'studio' to build pots for a local festival in which people would purchase pots to 'throw down and break during a celebration' only to be recycled again for a future use/celebration. The pots he noted were well made, almost perfect in symmetry despite the hand held and crude tools used to spin the pots. The artisan stacked the pots on end creating 'racks' of pots that overtook the public space of this small settlement. This was taken when Robert Vickery and his wife were preparing for their trip around the world. This was one of the most dangerous places in the United States and in Los Angeles, which still suffers from poverty and crime, and was constructed by a mailman, not a trained artist. He built these towers from the trash from others with no pragmatic use but symbolic in an area that had little hope. That art exists despite the troubles all around the artist and his community. -- Robert L. Vickery

The challenge in high rise living is to put all the main rooms in one sequence from the entry hall, living room, and dining area and beyond. Linear grouping of spaces delineated by the columns (not necessarily for structural purposes) and ornamental mantel connecting the columns with a pass through above. The columns were faux finished and were purchased from an older building - at the time a fairly new design approach. -- Robert L. Vickery

This church of a later era displays a beautiful fountain and cascading stairwell design. The designer of the staircase was a combination of rococo and neoclassical design elements. The Staircase of the Theological Virtues was conceived by Carlos Amarante. The idea of moving through time and space was a modern notion and the staircase is exemplary of that change in approach to the church - as opposed to simply moving in a straight line into a building and drawn to a final destination. The process of getting to the destination was as much of importance as the arriving at the front door of the church. -- Robert L. Vickery

... an ancient, walled arboretum in the Centro region of Portugal and home to one of the finest dendrological collections in Europe. ... Buçaco Forest was first settled in the 6th century by friars from a nearby Benedictine monastery; five hundred years later the Bishops of Coimbra took possession of the forest and in 1628 donated it to the Order of Discalced Carmelites. ... In 2004 Portugal submitted Buçaco Forest to UNESCO's tentative list of World Heritage Sites. -- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bu%C3%A7aco_Forest

Roman Temple of Évora, general view
Vickery, Robert L. (American architect and university professor)

The temple is believed to have been constructed around the first century A.D., in honour of Augustus, who was venerated as a god during and after his rule. ... The temple was destroyed during the 5th century by invading Germanic peoples. ... Although the Roman temple of Évora is often called the Temple of Diana, any association with the Roman goddess of hunt stems not from archaeology but from a legend created in the 17th century by [a] Portuguese priest. -- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Temple_of_%C3%89vora

Campo del Moro (the "Field of the Moor") is the huge urban park located directly behind the Palacio Real in Madrid Spain. Once a private playground for the Royal family, Campo del Moro today is popular destination for residents and visitors to Madrid. It features English style gardens, fountains, statues and natural woodlands. It dates back to Moorish times and was more recently the royal hunting grounds. -- https://espanarusa.com/en/hedonist/ad/hedonist/categories/Soul/city_park/497686

The interior is as well studied because of the continued use of strict graphic stone patterns and the exquisite paintings that began to explore 3-d and perspective in the representations of biblical content. Alberti had a history of working with visual artists as part of his architectural programs. -- Robert L. Vickery

Navicella Fountain, Minor Basilica of St. Mary in Domnica alla Navicella¶still image¶1518/1931

The fountain was built in 1931 using the small marble vessel which was already here, built in 1518-19, possibly based on a drawing by Andrea Sansovino, on the orders of Poe Leo X Medici (whose coat of arms is on the base). The small vessel, a Roman galley, is inspired by the ancient vessel discovered in the vicinity of the Colosseum, according to legend, an offering to the goddess Isis, the protector of seafarers, made by some sailors who had escaped disaster. Remembered here in the fifteenth century, the vessel also gives its name to the church of Santa Maria in Domnica, or alla Navicella. In its current position, with the bow in the form an animal head, it is placed on a base inside an oval basin, in a flowerbed. -- http://www.leviedelgiubileo.it/?p=5058

A trullo (plural, trulli) is a traditional Apulian dry stone hut with a conical roof. Their style of construction is specific to the Itria Valley, in the Murge area of the Italian region of Apulia. Trulli generally were constructed as temporary field shelters and storehouses or, as permanent dwellings by small proprietors or agricultural labourers. In the town of Alberobello, in the province of Bari, whole districts contain dense concentrations of trulli. The golden age of trulli was the nineteenth century, especially its final decades, which were marked by the development of wine growing. -- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trullo

Vickery was drawn to this village because of the roof construction done without an architect or engineer at a time when there was no mortar available. He appreciated a roof line without an arch, that wasn't flat and was completely unique and repeated as homes for peasants originally and have survived for centuries. -- Robert L. Vickery

Rivanna Reservoir, Albemarle, Virginia, United States

The School of Architecture's Annual Regatta and Picnic started in 1972 with inspiration from Professor H. Kenneth White. White assigned his studio the project of designing cardboard boats that would be able to be propelled across the Rivanna Reservoir. In subsequent years, the regatta grew to be a school-wide event.
